E. POSSIBLE FOLLOW-UP QUESTIONS FROM INTERVIEWERS (WITH ANSWERS)

Q1. Why did you choose nested Map for balances?

=> It allows O(1) time lookup for any pair of users.
=> It also automatically keeps the balance simplified (net owed amount) instead of storing every individual split.

Q2. How would you support Exact or Percent split?

=> I would introduce the Strategy design pattern with an interface SplitStrategy and concrete classes
like EqualSplitStrategy, ExactSplitStrategy, etc. Then inject the strategy while adding expense.

Q3. Is this design thread-safe?
=> No, currently it is not.
=> For production, I would use ConcurrentHashMap and synchronize the addDebt() method
or use locks while updating balances.

Q4. What if two users owe each other?
=> In a real system, we can simplify by keeping only net amount
(e.g., if Jishnu owes Madhan 400 and Madhan owes Jishnu 1000, then we keep Madhan owes Jishnu 600).

Q5. How would you persist this data?
I would use a relational database like PostgreSQL. User, Group, GroupMember, Expense, and a Balance table (or graph for debts).
Redis can be used for caching hot balances.

Q6. Can this handle users belonging to multiple groups?
Yes, because balances are maintained at the user level, not group level.
This matches how real Splitwise works.












